299&ndash;369. doi:10.1163/156853210X546509</li>

<li>Kjellberg, Paul, 1994, &ldquo;Skepticism, Truth, and the Good
Life: A Comparison of Zhuangzi and Sextus Empiricus&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy East and West</em>, 44(1): 111&ndash;133.
doi:10.2307/1399806</li>

<li>Kjellberg, Paul and P. J. Ivanhoe, 1996, <em>Essays on Skepticism,
Relativism, and Ethics in the Zhuangzi</em>, Albany, NY: State
University of New York Press.</li>

<li>Lai, Karyn L., 2022a, &ldquo;Freedom and Agency in the
Zhuangzi&#8239;: Navigating Life&rsquo;s Constraints&rdquo;,
<em>British Journal for the History of Philosophy</em>, 30(1):
3&ndash;23. doi:10.1080/09608788.2021.1994366</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022b, &ldquo;Performance and Agency in the
<em>Zhuangzi</em>&rdquo;, in Chong 2022: 661&ndash;682 (ch. 28).
doi:10.1007/978-3-030-92331-0_28</li>

<li>Lai, Karyn L. and Wai Wai Chiu, 2014, &ldquo;<em>Ming</em> in the
<em>Zhuangzi Neipian</em>: Enlightened Engagement&rdquo;, <em>Journal
of Chinese Philosophy</em>, 40(3&ndash;4): 527&ndash;543.
doi:10.1111/1540-6253.12052</li>

<li>Legge, James (trans), 1891, <em>The Sacred Books of China: The
Texts of Taoism</em>, 2 volumes, (Sacred Books of the East
39&ndash;40), Oxford: Clarendon Press. Reprinted, New York: Dover,
1962.
 [<a href="https://archive.org/details/sacredbookschin00legggoog/page/n7/mode/2up" target="other">Legge (trans.) 1891 volume 1 available online</a>]
 [<a href="https://archive.org/details/sacredbooksofchi028287mbp/page/n7/mode/2up" target="other">Legge (trans.) 1891 available online</a>]</li>

<li>Liu, X., 1994, <em>Classifying the <span class="plain">Zhuangzi</span>
Chapters</em> (Michigan Monographs in
Chinese Studies: Volume 65), Ann Arbor, MI: University of Michigan
Center for Chinese Studies.
 [<a href="https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/7d278v985/download?locale=en" target="other">Liu 1994 available online</a>]</li>
 
<li>Lo Yuet Keung &#21214;&#24709;&#24375;, 1999, &ldquo;To Use or Not
to Use: The Idea of <em>Ming</em> in the <em>Zhuangzi</em>&rdquo;,
<em>Monumenta Serica</em>, 47(1): 149&ndash;168.
doi:10.1080/02549948.1999.11731326</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, &ldquo;The Authorship of the
Zhuangzi&rdquo;, in Chong 2022: 237&ndash;267 (ch. 11).
doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-92331-0_3</li>

<li>Mair, Victor H. (ed.), 1983, <em>Experimental Essays on
Chuang-tzu</em>, Honolulu: [published for] Center for Asian and
Pacific Studies [by] University of Hawai&rsquo;i Press.</li>

<li>M&ouml;ller [Moeller], Hans-Georg, 1999, &ldquo;Zhuangzi&rsquo;s
&lsquo;Dream of the Butterfly&rsquo;: A Daoist Interpretation&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy East and West</em>, 49(4): 439&ndash;450.
doi:10.2307/1399947</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, &ldquo;Humor and its Philosophical
Significance in the <em>Zhuangzi</em>&rdquo;, in Chong 2022:
287&ndash;304 (ch. 13). doi:10.1007/978-3-030-92331-0_13</li>

<li>Moeller, Hans-Georg and Paul J. D&rsquo;Ambrosio, 2017,
<em>Genuine Pretending: On the Philosophy of the Zhuangzi</em>, New
York: Columbia University Press.</li>

<li>Porat, Roy, 2022, &ldquo;Language in the <em>Zhuangzi</em>&rdquo;,
in Chong 2022: 237&ndash;267 (ch. 11).
doi:10.1007/978-3-030-92331-0_11</li>

<li>Raphals, Lisa, 1994, &ldquo;Skeptical Strategies in the
&lsquo;Zhuangzi&rsquo; and &lsquo;Theaetetus&rsquo;&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy East and West</em>, 44(3): 501&ndash;526.
doi:10.2307/1399738</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, &ldquo;The <em>Zhuangzi</em> on
<em>Ming</em> (&#21629;)&rdquo;, in Chong 2022: 217&ndash;233 (ch.
10). doi:10.1007/978-3-030-92331-0_10</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, &ldquo;Neuroscientific and Cognitive
Perspectives on the <em>Zhuangzi</em>&rdquo; in Chong 2022:
683&ndash;702 (ch. 29). doi:10.1007/978-3-030-92331-0_29</li>

<li>Robins, Dan, 2011, &ldquo;&lsquo;It Goes Beyond
Skill&rsquo;&rdquo;, in Fraser, Robins, and O&rsquo;Leary 2011:
105&ndash;123 (ch. 5).</li>

<li>Roth, Harold D., 1991, &ldquo;Who Compiled the Chuang-Tzu&rdquo;,
in <em>Chinese Texts and Philosophical Contexts: Essays Dedicated to
Angus C. Graham</em>, Henry Rosemont (ed.), (Critics and Their Critics
1), La Salle, IL: Open Court, 82&ndash;128.</li>

<li>Roth, Harold D. (ed.), 2003, <em>A Companion to Angus C.
Graham&rsquo;s Chuang Tzu</em> (Monograph of the Society for Asian and
Comparative Philosophy, No. 20), Honolulu: University of Hawai&rsquo;i
Press.</li>

<li>Shang, Ge Ling, 2006, <em>Liberation as Affirmation: The
Religiosity of Zhuangzi and Nietzsche</em>, (SUNY Series in Chinese
Philosophy and Culture), Albany, NY: State University of New York
Press.</li>

<li>Soles, Deborah H. and David E. Soles, 1998, &ldquo;Fish Traps and
Rabbit Snares: Zhuangzi on Judgement, Truth and Knowledge&rdquo;,
<em>Asian Philosophy</em>, 8(3): 149&ndash;164.
doi:10.1080/09552369808575481</li>

<li>Stevenson, Frank W., 2006, &ldquo;Zhuangzi&rsquo;s <em>Dao</em> as
Background Noise&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy East and West</em>, 56(2):
301&ndash;331. doi:10.1353/pew.2006.0025</li>

<li>Sturgeon, Donald, 2015, &ldquo;<em>Zhuangzi</em>, Perspectives,
and Greater Knowledge&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy East and West</em>,
65(3): 892&ndash;917. doi:10.1353/pew.2015.0064</li>

<li>Sun Yirang&nbsp;&#23403;&#35410;&#35698;, and &#22696;&#32735;.
1965. &#23450;&#26412;&#22696;&#23376;&#38290;&#35393;
(&#19990;&#30028;&#26360;&#23616;: &#21488;&#21271;).</li>

<li>Van Norden, Bryan W., 1996, &ldquo;Competing Interpretations of
the Inner Chapters of the &lsquo;Zhuangzi&rsquo;&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy East and West</em>, 46(2): 247.
doi:10.2307/1399405</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016. &ldquo;Zhuangzi&rsquo;s Ironic
Detachment and Political Commitment&rdquo;, <em>Dao: a Journal of
Comparative Philosophy</em>, 15: 1&ndash;17.</li>

<li>Walker, Stephen C., 2019, &ldquo;Boundless Ways: Undoing
<em>D&agrave;o</em> in the <em>Zhu&#257;ngz&#464;</em>&rdquo;, PhD
dissertation, The University of Chicago.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, &ldquo;&lsquo;Are You Really Right?
Am I Really Wrong?&rsquo;: Responding to Debates in
<em>Zhu&#257;ngz&#464;</em> 2&rdquo;, <em>Dao: A Journal of
Comparative Philosophy</em>, 21(4): 533&ndash;548.
doi:10.1007/s11712-022-09851-x</li>

<li>Wang Xianqian, 1987, <em>Zhuangzi ji jie</em> (<em>Xin bian zhu zi
ji cheng</em>), Beijing: Zhonghua Shu ju.</li>

<li>Wong, David B., 2005, &ldquo;Zhuangzi and the Obsession with Being
Right&rdquo;, <em>History of Philosophy Quarterly</em>, 22(2):
91&ndash;107.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, &ldquo;Constructive Skepticism in the
<em>Zhuangzi</em>&rdquo;, in Chong 2022: 639&ndash;660 (ch. 27).
doi:10.1007/978-3-030-92331-0_27</li>

<li>Yearley, Lee, 1983, &ldquo;The Perfected Person in the Radical
Chuang-tzu&rdquo;, in Mair 1983: 125&ndash;139.</li>

<li>Ziporyn, Brook, 2013, <em>Beyond Oneness and Difference: Li and
Coherence in Chinese Buddhist Thought and Its Antecedents</em>, State
University of New York Press: Albany.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012, <em>Ironies of Oneness and Difference
Coherence in Early Chinese Thought: Prolegomena to the Study of
Li</em>, Albany, NY: State University of New York Press.</li>
</ul>
